# Terminal Execution Rules

1. NEVER pipe python or test execution commands into `tail`, `head`, `less`, or log-limiting utilities (e.g., `2>&1 | tail -20`). This causes output buffering, blinds your context window, and leads to infinite execution loops.
2. ALWAYS execute python scripts and inline snippets natively so that standard output (stdout) and standard error (stderr) streams stream to the terminal in real time.
3. When writing one-off inline python strings (`python3 -c "..."`), always include `flush=True` in print statements to ensure the terminal outputs progress instantly.
4. If a script appears to take a long time (such as loading PyTorch or machine learning models), write brief, incremental status print statements so progress can be monitored.

# Background Processes & Long-Running Servers

1. When launching a background process or server using `&` or `nohup`, ALWAYS disconnect standard input by adding `< /dev/null` at the end of the background statement. (Example: `nohup python3 server.py > server.log 2>&1 < /dev/null &`). If you omit `< /dev/null`, the terminal session will hang indefinitely.
2. NEVER assume a background server is running successfully just because it echoed a Process ID (PID). 
3. ALWAYS verify your background tasks. Immediately after launching a background process, chain a sleep command followed by a log check or process check (e.g., `& sleep 2 && cat /tmp/server.log` or `curl localhost:port`). This ensures you catch immediate startup crashes (like port-in-use or missing dependencies) instead of looping.

# Script Execution & Inline Code Rules

1. NEVER execute multi-line Python code blocks directly in the terminal using `python3 -c "..."`. Multi-line strings break pseudo-terminal (pty) quote parsing, leaving the shell hanging indefinitely waiting for closing inputs.
2. ALWAYS write any Python script longer than a single line to a temporary file (e.g., `temp_test.py`), execute that file directly (`python3 temp_test.py`), and delete it immediately afterward.
3. Single-line `-c` execution is allowed ONLY for simple imports or version checks (e.g., `python3 -c "import torch; print(torch.__version__)"`).

# Verification & Testing Rules

1. NEVER assume code works without empirical proof. Simply checking that a file saved or that "the logic looks sound" is insufficient. Every code change must be validated by running a test script, compiling, or executing a dry-run pass.
2. ALWAYS execute targeted testing before claiming a task is complete. If you modify a specific function or module, write or run an isolated test script targeting that exact logic to verify both success states and edge cases (e.g., empty inputs, malformed structures).
3. Do not rely solely on unit tests; perform an integration check. After confirming that an isolated fix works, run a brief end-to-end or integration pass (e.g., running the actual server file briefly or hitting the specific API endpoint) to ensure your changes didn't break downstream modules.
4. When writing inline test snippets, explicitly print the expected vs. actual outcomes. Do not just print "Done". Print clear, comparative debugging statements (e.g., `print(f"Expected: {expected} | Got: {actual}")`) so the output in the terminal provides undeniable evidence of correctness.
5. If a test fails, you must read the traceback completely. Never blindly re-run the same execution command hoping for a different result. Inspect the stack trace, locate the exact file and line number causing the failure, modify the implementation, and then re-test.
6. Keep the workspace clean. If you create temporary mock files, dummy images, or scratchpad text files to verify a feature, you must delete them before declaring the task finished. Do not leave temporary artifacts in the repository.

# File Generation & Heredoc Restrictions

1. NEVER use shell Heredocs (`<<'EOF'`, `cat > file`) to generate or overwrite files in the terminal. Multi-line heredoc string routing routinely deadlocks pseudo-terminal (pty) input streams.
2. ALWAYS use your native system file tools (like `write_to_file`) to create or modify code, test scripts, or configuration files. Only use the terminal to *execute* commands, never to author file contents.